'''Nogita Shrine''' (のぎたじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Higashi-Ahe, Takatsuki-chō, {{ill|lt=Nagahama|Q844130|WD=Q844130|1=Nagahama, Shiga}}, {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|WD=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|lt=Homudawake|Q317997|WD=Q317997|lt=Homudawake-no-Mikoto|1=Emperor Ōjin}}
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ame-tsukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}

=== Shrine crest ===
Left triple tomoe

=== History ===
Founding period unknown. It is a candidate shrine (Shikinaisha ronsha) for "Nogita Shrine" in {{ill|lt=Ika District|Q1042353|WD=Q1042353|1=Ika District, Shiga}}, {{ill|lt=Ōmi Province|Q843882|WD=Q843882|1=Ōmi Province}}, listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}<ref>Other candidates include a {{ill|lt=Nogita Shrine (Nagahama, Takatsuki-chō Higashimononobe)|UNKNOWN|lt=shrine of the same name}} in Higashimononobe, Takatsuki-chō, same city.</ref>. It was under the protection of Ahe Awaji-no-kami, a vassal of the {{ill|lt=Azai clan|Q1872031|WD=Q1872031|1=Azai clan}}, but was lost to fire in the {{ill|lt=Battle of Shizugatake|Q225562|WD=Q225562|1=Battle of Shizugatake}}. The current shrine buildings were built in {{ill|lt=1797|Q7820|WD=Q7820|1=1797}} (Kansei 9). In {{ill|lt=1876|Q7766|WD=Q7766|1=1876}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 9), it was ranked as a {{ill|lt=Sonsha|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Festivals ===
* Annual festival (Moroko Festival) - September 13
* {{ill|lt=Okonai|Q11291908|WD=Q11291908|1=Okonai}} - February 8

